bystanders who were quietly knitting for the duration; rather, they actively participated in wartime society, served their country in a variety of ways, made sacrifices, and were deeply affected by the vagaries of war. Incorporating the experiences of Newfoundland with those of Canada, and looking at girls as well as women, the volume enriches our knowledge of an important era in Canadian nation building and takes a step towards writing women into the historical narratives of the First World War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, Kristine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuley, Margot I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlassford, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlassford, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHallett, Vicki S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorton, Desmond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorman, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuiney, Linda J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShaw, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShaw, Amy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStirling, Terry Bishop, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStreet, Kori, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTector, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilde, Terry,